# Resume Library
# Shows how Copilot can organize and enrich a document library full of resumes —
# extracting names, suggesting columns, categorizing candidates, and building
# a structured hiring pipeline without manual data entry.

[section: setup]

Verify the Candidates document library exists and contains uploaded resume files
before running the demo. The library should have at least a few resumes but no
metadata columns yet — this demo builds them live.

[navigate: https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

[section: demo]

[navigate: https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/Candidates/]

We're starting with a document library full of resumes. Each file was uploaded as-is
— no metadata, no columns, no organization. Just raw files. Let's use Copilot to
turn this into a structured hiring pipeline without touching a single document
manually.

[pause]

[open-chat]

First, let's pull the candidate names directly out of the files and populate a column.

[prompt: Extract the person's name from each file and add them to a Candidate Name column.]

[wait]

Copilot read each document, found the person's name, created the column, and stamped
every row. That's the kind of manual work that used to take an afternoon.

[pause]

Now let's ask Copilot what other columns would make sense for organizing these files.

[prompt: Suggest some more columns to organize these resumes.]

[wait]

Notice that Copilot is reasoning about what matters for a hiring library — not just
generic metadata. Let's take one of those suggestions and go further.

[pause]

[prompt: Categorize if this candidate is best suited for an HR, Marketing, Finance, Sales, or Engineering role.]

[wait]

Copilot read each resume and made a role judgment based on the content. These
candidates are now organized by the work they're actually suited for — not by
file name or upload date.

[pause]

Let's group the view so we can see candidates by role at a glance.

[prompt: Group the candidates by role.]

[wait]

Now the library is readable as a hiring pipeline. Let's add some operational logic.

[pause]

[prompt: Send me an email any time a new Engineering candidate is added.]

[wait]

That's an automation trigger set up in natural language. No Power Automate canvas,
no connector configuration. Just a request.

[pause]

Let's add a tracking field so the team can manage candidate status.

[prompt: Add a choice field to track whether we've reviewed the candidate, sent them for an interview, have offered, and they accepted or declined.]

[wait]

Now we have a workflow stage column. Every candidate has a status we can filter and
report on.

[pause]

[prompt: Can you create a table summarizing how many candidates of each type we found so far?]

[wait]

A live summary from the library contents. Good for a hiring manager who wants a
quick headcount before a meeting.

[pause]

[prompt: Can you style the library columns to be clearly differentiated across target role and hiring status?]

[wait]

Color coding the rows by role and status — so the most important information jumps
out visually. The library went from a pile of files to a functional hiring tracker
in a single chat session.

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/resume-library.png]

[section: reset]

The demo created columns and formatting rules on the Candidates library. To reset,
delete the added columns (Candidate Name, Role, Status) and remove any applied
views or formatting.

[navigate: https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/Candidates/]
